<H2>Year 2 Ontologies</H2>

<P>
These ontologies have been developed or are under development at ISI
for the HPKB year 2 battlespace problem. 
</P>

<H3> PLANET</H3>

This is an ontology for plans, available in 
<A HREF="sources/ontologies/planet/planet.loom"> Loom </A>
and <A HREF="sources/ontologies/planet/planet.ke"> Cyc </A>
format, with KIF to follow. The Cyc version was developed in 
collaboration with Cycorp and Teknowledge:
<A HREF="sources/ontologies/planet/alignment">here is a document</A>
explaining the alignment process. At the moment, the Loom version
is the more complete.
<A HREF="http://www.isi.edu/~blythe/planet">Here</A> is a page
describing the ontology, with a pointer to a more detailed project
report.

<H3> Critiquer output ontology</H3>

This ontology of critiques, evaluations and estimates is for 
use to couch the output of the separate critiquers to the integration
module. 
<A HREF="sources/ontologies/output/evaluations.loom">Here</A>
it is as a loom document.
<A HREF="http://www.isi.edu/~blythe/evaluation-ontology">Here</A>
is a page describing the ontology.


<H3>Other ontologies coming to this page soon</H3>
<LU>
<LI> Resource ontology
<LI> Ontology of constraints on plans, for evaluating COAs.
</UL>

<H2><A NAME="on-line"> Ontologies Browsable On-Line </A></H2>
The ontologies below can be browsed on-line via the <A
HREF="http://www.isi.edu/isd/ontosaurus.html"> Ontosaurus </A>
browser.  Since some of the ontologies contain content that was
derived from copyrighted material, browser access is password
protected.  Please use the same username and password you used
to access this page (since Ontosaurus runs on a separate server,
you will have to enter them again).  If you have any problems
accessing these ontologies, please send mail to
<A HREF=mailto:hans@@isi.edu>hans@@isi.edu</A>.

<p>
To browse an ontology, select one of the links below and supply the
necessary username and password.  Once the initial Ontosaurus browser
window has come up, select the appropriate ontology/theory from the <strong>
Theory </strong> menu in the navigation pane.  By default, the merged
<code> BATTLE-SPACE </code> ontology is selected from which you can
see everything defined in the upper, middle, and lower levels.
However, if, for example, you are only interested in vehicles, you can
select the <code> LAND-VEHICLES </code> theory to not see other irrelevant
information.

<p>
To find a particular concept or relation, type its
name (or part of it) in the input box and then click on the <strong>
Find </strong> button, for example, type <code> M113 </code> to find
information about M113s.  If relevant information
could be found, it will be displayed with mouse-sensitive links which
you can click on to start browsing.  Alternatively, you can select a
particular ontology/theory and then click the <strong>Show</strong> button
which will display the top-level concepts in this theory and various
related information which you can use to start browsing.

<UL>
  <LI> <A HREF="http://sevak.isi.edu:8500/loom/shuttle.html">
       Merged Battle Space Ontology </A> (theory name <code>
       BATTLE-SPACE </code>).  This ontology consists of the following
       components (currently, all links below lead to the same browser
       entry point):
       <UL>
         <LI> <A HREF="http://sevak.isi.edu:8500/loom/shuttle.html">
              CYC/Sensus Upper Level </A> (theory name <code>
              CYC-SENSUS-UPPER </code>)
         <LI> <A HREF="http://sevak.isi.edu:8500/loom/shuttle.html">
              CYC Vehicle Middle Level </A> (theory name <code>
              CYC-VEHICLES </code>)
         <LI> <A HREF="http://sevak.isi.edu:8500/loom/shuttle.html">
              Land Vehicles </A> (theory name <code> LAND-VEHICLES </code>)
         <LI> <A HREF="http://sevak.isi.edu:8500/loom/shuttle.html">
              Geographical Features for Workarounds </A> (theory name
              <code> FEATURES </code>)
         <LI> <A HREF="http://sevak.isi.edu:8500/loom/shuttle.html">
              Engineering Equipment </A> (theory name <code>
              ENGINEERING-EQUIPMENT </code>)
       </UL>
</UL>


<H2><A NAME="okbc"> Ontologies Accessible Via OKBC </A></H2>

We have an OKBC server running from which you can access the latest
version of the <A HREF="http://sevak.isi.edu:8500/loom/shuttle.html">
Merged Battle Space Ontology </A>.  To connect to the server use the
address <code> sevak.isi.edu </code> and choose a port between
<code>8995</code> and <code>9005</code>.  Since the server
implementation of the standard OKBC release does not support
multi-threading, each client has to connect at a different port.
Therefore, if you connect but do not get any response after some time,
please try a different port in the above range to see whether that
fixes the problem.  Please make sure to always close connections with
<code>okbc:close-connection</code> so that the port gets freed up for
somebody else to use.  This scheme is somewhat fragile, so, if you
have any problems connecting or any other questions regarding the OKBC
server, please send mail to <A
HREF=mailto:hans@@isi.edu>hans@@isi.edu</A>.

<p>
Before you start connecting, you should probably <A HREF="#on-line">
browse </A> the ontology via Ontosaurus to find out about names of
concepts and slots/relations.  For simplicity, the ontology available
via our OKBC server does not have explicitly represented units, thus,
if, for example, you see a speed listed in Ontosaurus as 48km/h, you will get
the bare 48 back when you retrieve the particular slot value via OKBC
(see example).  The unit used for a particular slot/relation can be
retrieved via the <code> output-unit </code> relation (see example).

<p>
Below is a simple example dialog between a Lisp-based OKBC client and
our OKBC server.  User input at the <code>USER(n):</code> prompt is
shown in <strong>bold</strong> face.

<p>
<blockquote>
<pre>
;; You have to define the following two packages to be able to properly
;; qualify frame names.  All frame name symbols in the battle space
;; ontlogy have to be explicitly qualified with 'BS', for example, to
;; refer to the class 'M60' you have to use 'BS::M60':
<strong>USER(1): (defpackage "LOOM")</strong>
#&lt;The LOOM package&gt;
<strong>USER(2): (defpackage "BATTLE-SPACE" (:nicknames "BS"))</strong>
#&lt;The BATTLE-SPACE package&gt;
<strong>USER(3): (setq netcon
           (okbc:establish-connection
            'ok-back::simple-network-connection
            :initargs '(:host "sevak.isi.edu" :port 9003)))</strong>

;;; Persistent Network OKBC connection established.
#&lt;OK-BACK:SIMPLE-NETWORK-CONNECTION @@ #x256fdaa&gt;
<strong>USER(5): (setq bskb (okbc:find-kb 'BS::BATTLE-SPACE :connection netcon))</strong>
#&lt;OK-BACK::LOOM-KB-NETWORK-KB
  BATTLE-SPACE on stream #&lt;BIDIRECTIONAL-TERMINAL-STREAM
                           to [sevak.isi.edu/9003] fd 9&gt;:NIL
  @@ #x2587162&gt;
<strong>USER(6): (okbc:get-slot-value 'BS::M60 'BS::MAX-SPEED-ON-ROAD :kb bskb  :slot-type :template)</strong>
48
T
<strong>USER(7): (okbc:get-slot-value 'BS::M60 'BS::MAX-STEP :kb bskb :slot-type :template)</strong>
0.91
T
<strong>USER(8): (okbc:get-slot-value 'BS::MAX-SPEED-ON-ROAD 'BS::OUTPUT-UNIT :kb bskb :slot-type :own)</strong>
"km/h"
T
<strong>USER(9): (okbc:get-slot-value 'BS::MAX-STEP 'BS::OUTPUT-UNIT :kb bskb :slot-type :own)</strong>
"m"
T
<strong>USER(10): (okbc:get-class-superclasses 'BS::M60 :kb bskb)</strong>
(#&lt;OK-BACK:FRAME-HANDLE 415894776:2 @@ #x259c37a&gt;
 #&lt;OK-BACK:FRAME-HANDLE 415894776:3 @@ #x259c472&gt;
 #&lt;OK-BACK:FRAME-HANDLE 415894776:4 @@ #x259c56a&gt; ...)
T
;; Please be sure to close the connection at the end, so the port gets freed
;; up for somebody else to use:
<strong>USER(11): (okbc:close-connection netcon)</strong>

;;; Closed simple-network-connection #&lt;OK-BACK:SIMPLE-NETWORK-CONNECTION @@ #x256fdaa&gt;
NIL
<strong>USER(12): </strong>
</pre>
</blockquote>

